-- RTS Futures Advance Amid Signs of U.S. Economic Recovery: Russia Overnight
-- B y   H a l i a   P a v l i v a   a n d   L e o n   L a z a r o f f
-- 2011-12-26T00:10:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-26/rts-futures-rise-amid-signs-of-u-s-recovery-russia-overnight.html
RTS  futures  rose and Russian stocks
gained in  New York  last week as signs the world’s largest
economy is recovering buoyed oil while President  Dmitry Medvedev ’s proposed reforms failed to end anti-government
protests.  The  Bloomberg Russia-US 14 Index  of Russian companies
traded in the U.S. climbed 0.4 percent to 91.65 on Dec. 23,
extending the weekly advance to 2.1 percent, the most since the
five days ended Dec. 2.  Yandex NV , operator of Russia’s most
popular Internet search engine, led gains Dec. 23 after boosting
its market share.  OAO Lukoil (LUKOY) , Russia’s largest non-state oil
producer, rose to its highest level since Dec. 7.  An increase in U.S. industrial purchases and a gain in  home
construction  helped push crude up 6.6 percent last week, the
largest advance since Oct. 28. Signs that growth in the biggest
oil consuming country may accelerate improved the outlook for
Russia, the world’s largest energy exporter. Russian Prime
Minister  Vladimir Putin  and President Medvedev faced new mass
protests throughout the country on Dec. 24.  “The saving grace for Russian equities the past few months
has been that U.S. numbers are indicating a modest but
continuing recovery,”  Chris Weafer , chief strategist at Troika
Dialog, Russia’s oldest investment bank, said in a phone
interview from  London . “If oil hadn’t remained stronger than
expected this year considering slow global growth, Russian
equities would be much worse off than they already are.”  Government Protests  At least 30,000 people gathered in Moscow on Dec. 24 over
alleged election fraud, police said. The event organizers said
up to 120,000 people attended the rally in Moscow. Tens of
thousands people joined street protests throughout the country,
in all of its eight time zones from Kaliningrad on the  Baltic
Sea  to Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk on North Pacific Ocean,  Kommersant 
newspaper reported.  Former Finance Minister  Alexei Kudrin , who resigned in
September after a clash with Medvedev, addressed protestors in
Moscow on Dec. 24, backing their demand for a repeat of the
disrupted parliamentary poll and warned of a “revolution”
unless the government calms popular anger.  Putin’s spokesperson Dmitry Peskov said Putin is “beyond
competition” as presidential candidate in March vote because
majority of voters support him and protestors are “minority,”
RBC daily reported on Dec. 25, citing Peskov’s interview with
 Agence France-Presse .  Medvedev’s draft bill aimed at making registration of
parties and running for president easier was the authorities’
first concessions following the Dec. 4 protests.  RTS Futures  Russia’s  Micex (INDEXCF)  Index, which has lost 18 percent in 2011,
 trades  at 4.6 times analysts’ earnings estimates for member
companies, the cheapest valuation of the 21 major  emerging
markets  tracked by Bloomberg. Brent oil, the benchmark for
Russian crude, settled on Dec. 23 at $107.96 a barrel and has
gained 14 percent this year.  Futures on the dollar-denominated RTS index expiring in
March rose 0.7 percent to 138,300 on Dec. 23.  Russia cut its benchmark rate to ease borrowing costs to
shield the country from a global slump. The refinancing rate was
lowered to 8 percent from 8.25 percent, effective today, Bank
Rossii said in a statement on its website Dec. 23.  Yandex  increased 4 percent to $19.96 on Dec. 23, bringing
the weekly gain to 14 percent, its largest since the five days
ending Oct. 14. Liveintenet.ru, an Internet-service provider and
researcher, said that Yandex’s share of the Russian search
market rose to 60.9 percent last week, from 60.7 percent in the
previous week.  Lukoil gained 1.4 percent to $53 on Dec. 23, boosting its
advance to 5.1 percent last week.  Shares  in Moscow rose 0.3
percent to 1,639.20 rubles, or the equivalent of $52.62. One ADR
represents one ordinary share.  Commodities Gain  Urals crude,  Russia ’s chief export blend, gained 0.2
percent on Dec. 23 to $109.19. The Standard & Poor’s GSCI index
of 24 raw materials advanced 0.1 percent, bringing the weekly
advance to 4.5 percent.  Medvedev submitted a draft bill to make it easier to
register parties and run for president. Under his proposal,
parties would require 500 members from at least half of Russia’s
regions, down from 50,000, Medvedev’s office said Dec. 23 on its
website. Independent candidates for president in 2018 elections
would need to collect 300,000 signatures, down from 2 million.  Polyus Gold International Ltd. , Russia’s largest gold
miner, dropped in U.S. trading after gold fell for a third day
on Dec. 23 and Valery Senko was elected as chairman of the
company’s Russian unit replacing billionaire  Mikhail Prokhorov ,
who holds a stake in Polyus and is challenging Putin in the
March elections. Polyus lost 3.1 percent in New York to $2.81.  Mobile Phones   OAO Mobile TeleSystems (MBT) , Russia’s largest mobile-phone
operator, fell 1.5 percent to $14.95 in New York on Dec. 23
after the company cut roaming tariffs for its clients, offering
free incoming calls of up to 10 minutes anywhere in the world.
About 5 percent of the company’s annual revenue comes from
roaming services, according to Uralsib Financial Corp.  OAO Rostelecom , Russia’s dominant fixed-line phone company,
rose 1.8 percent to $28.82, gaining 2 percent from the previous
week. Rostelecom’s board approved guarantees on loans to Sky
Link, a wireless Internet and telephone operator it plans to
buy, allowing local banks to release 1.71 billion rubles ($55
million) in financing to Sky Link, Interfax news agency reported
on Dec. 23.  The  RTS Index  declined 0.1 percent on Dec. 23 to 1,394.12,
paring its gain for the week to 1.5 percent. The 30-stock Micex
Index lost 0.7 percent to 1,376.11, bringing its loss for the
week to 0.5 percent.  Volatility Eases  The  RTS Volatility Index , which measures expected swings in
the index futures, dropped for a seventh day, falling 6.7
percent to 39.75 points, its lowest closing level since Sept. 1.
The  Market Vectors Russia ETF (RSX) , a U.S.-traded fund that holds
Russian shares, rose 0.3 percent to $26.99.  The Micex’s 18 percent decline this year compares with a 17
percent slide for  Brazil ’s  Bovespa (IBOV)  index, which trades at 10.2
times estimated earnings, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The  Shanghai Composite Index (SHCOMP)  trades at 10.6 times
estimated earnings, and the  BSE India Sensitive Index (SENSEX)  has a
ratio of 13.7.  To contact the reporters on this story:
